After the bombings in Nairobi and Dar, the US retaliated by striking Sudan's pharmaceutical factory, sparking outrage.
Many believed Clinton's actions were to divert attention from his personal issues.
Sudan condemned the attacks, claiming the factory produced medicine, not weapons.
The Sudanese government vowed to file complaints with the UN and Arab League.
Meanwhile, citizens criticized the US for interfering in internal affairs.
Despite American accusations, Sudan denied involvement with terrorism.
The situation escalated as Sudan called for a fact-finding mission and vowed to prove the factory's innocence.
Sudanese citizens remained skeptical about the allegations.
